  "prompt": "What is the difference between negative ion and electron?",
  "response": "Negative ions and electrons are related concepts, but they are not the same thing. Here\u2019s the distinction:\n\n### **Electron**:\n- An **electron** is a fundamental subatomic particle with a negative electric charge.\n- It is one of the building blocks of atoms, along with protons and neutrons.\n- Electrons are elementary particles, meaning they are not composed of smaller particles.\n- Electrons exist freely in space or are bound to atoms in orbitals.\n- The charge of an electron is \\( -1.6 \\times 10^{-19} \\) coulombs.\n\n### **Negative Ion**:\n- A **negative ion** is an atom or molecule that has gained one or more extra electrons.\n- It carries a net negative charge because the number of electrons exceeds the number of protons in the nucleus.\n- Negative ions are not elementary particles; they are created when neutral atoms or molecules gain electrons.\n- Examples include \\( \\text{Cl}^- \\) (chloride ion) or \\( \\text{O}^{2-} \\) (oxide ion).\n\n### **Key Difference**:\n- An **electron** is a single, fundamental particle with a negative charge.\n- A **negative ion** is an atom or molecule that has gained one or more electrons, resulting in a net negative charge.\n\nIn summary, an electron is a particle, while a negative ion is an atom or molecule that has acquired extra electrons.",
